<br>
The only sad part, as I said, is that cowards often aren't too bright and take a while to get the message... which can hurt in the meantime.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ignore them...&quot;  I say no, unless you're one of the rare people who can really just shut it off and not care.  For everybody else, you're not ignoring the assaults, you're absorbing and being harmed by them without protecting or responding.  <br>
<br>
If you were practicing this approach in a martial arts class (aikido is my personal love because it teaches strength, awareness and RESPONSES to violence, not tricks for how to break arms), you'd stand there looking away while your partner punched you over and over.  You'd get hurt.  Badly hurt, if your partner didn't like you.  And in the end, it would only end because your attacker walked away, leaving you an injured victim and leaving you open for tomorrow's practice session.<br>
<br>
I think that what I do to handle this kind of thing isn't going to work well for you.  Why not?  Two reasons.<br>
<br>
First, because I'm 40 (in two months) and I just don't give a rip about a lot of things that you still do.  When I was 14???  I was a freaked-out, pathetic nerd.  Now, I'm just a pathetic nerd and a whole lot of stuff just doesn't matter anymore.  Funny looking?  Inconvenient?  Old?  Hell, yes, I am... what, am I supposed to disagree with the ridiculously obvious???  What I can't change, I just accept nowadays.<br>
<br>
The other reason is that for whatever reason, folks just do not mess with me in person.  It's partly appearance (I'm not real tall but I'm fairly... &quot;thick&quot;, sorta brick-shaped), and partly... I have no idea.  I'm amazingly unviolent and unthreatening in spirit, but people just leave me alone.<br>
<br>
But there are a couple of things to think about anyway...<br>
<br>
1.  Accept and understand what they are doing.  If they bitch at you, stand up and bow.  Or, cry happily, &quot;YES!!!  I ALONE CONTROL THE BUSES NOW.  YOU ARE AT MY MERCY.&quot;  Do make fun of it because it's a stupid assault.  You have every right to be on the bus, and it's not because of you that the buses are late.  They're late because they leave too late to do all the things they need to do.  If you must react, react with humor rather than defensive resentment.  <br>
<br>
Will they like you?  Hell no, they'll think you're a freak.  But you know what?  They already think that or they wouldn't be casing on you.  If you react with visible humor, there IS somebody out there who will eventually see that and become your friend for it... just not one of the fools who's picking on you.  If you react with a victimized silence, you'll miss an opportunity to find an ally in your life.<br>
<br>
2.  Learn by practicing #1 to use humor to repair your soul.  While you acknowledge the attacks, you can feel yourself be strong in their face, and that feels good.  Personal strength and cleverness build on themselves.<br>
<br>
3.  Go find an aikido dojo that has teen classes.  You're plenty old enough to go to class, do the motions, learn to fall, learn to throw others, and suddenly realize that all that physical work is teaching you how to handle verbal attacks and threats just as much as the physical ones.<br>
<br>
If you learn to be strong in the center of your body, you will eventually learn to create a strong center in your soul.  And when that happens, the taunts will become wind and rain on the roof rather than something that threatens your safety.<br>
